{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2018}} {{short description|2006 GBA action role-playing video game}} {{Infobox video game | title = Back to Stone | image = Back to stone boxart.jpg | caption = North American boxart | developer = Hidden Floor<ref>[http://www.hiddenfloor.com Hidden Floor website]</ref> | publisher = {{nowrap|{{vgrelease|EU|[[Neko Entertainment]] / [[Big Ben Interactive]]}}}}{{nowrap|{{vgrelease|NA|Graffiti Entertainment / [[O~3 Entertainment]]}}}} | composer = [[Frédéric Motte]]<ref name="Composer">[http://backtostone.hiddenfloor.com/frmcont/contact.html ''Back to stone''{{'}}s official contact page]</ref> | platforms = [[Game Boy Advance]] | released = December 15, 2006 | genre = [[Action role-playing]], [[hack and slash]] | modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]] }}
'''''Back to Stone''''' is an [[action role-playing]]/[[hack and slash]] game using an [[Isometric graphics in video games and pixel art|isometric 3D perspective]] developed by French studio Hidden Floor.<ref name=OfficialNeko /> It was published by [[Neko Entertainment]] / [[Big Ben Interactive]] in Europe and by Graffiti Entertainment / [[O~3 Entertainment]] in North America.<ref name="OfficialNeko">{{cite web| url=http://www.e-neko.com/?p=1397 |title=Back to stone |publisher=[[Neko Entertainment]] |accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref> The music was composed by [[Frédéric Motte|Frédéric "Elmobo" Motte]].<ref name=Composer /> It was released for the [[Game Boy Advance]] on December 14, 2006.<ref name=OfficialNeko />
==Gameplay== The player controls a warrior who is mysteriously [[amnesiac]] and has been experimented on by demonic creatures. Players can move the character around the game's environments freely, jump around platforms, and fight enemies dynamically. Killed enemies turn to stone, which can then be moved around and used to solve puzzles. When the player's character is wounded, he transforms into a demonic monster, which improves his fighting capabilities.<ref name="Jeuxpo">{{cite web |title=Après plusieurs années de développement, Back to Stone arrive enfin sur GB A|trans-title=After many years in development, Back to Stone finally arrives on GBA |url=http://jeuxpo.com/game_test-2219.html |publisher=JeuXpo.com |accessdate=September 11, 2015 |language=French}}</ref><ref name="NSpin" /><ref name=Nexus />
The game does not feature any way to [[Saved game|save the player's progress]], which had been a standard feature of video games for many years by 2006. Instead, the game relies on [[Password (video gaming)|passwords]] to allow the player to return to the game where they had left off when they last turned off the console.<ref name="JustRPG">{{cite web |author=Felipe Faria Lemos |title=Reviews – Back to Stone |url=http://just-rpg.com/default.asp?pid=2310 |publisher=Just RPG |accessdate=September 11, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101217054337/http://just-rpg.com/default.asp?pid=2310 |archivedate=December 17, 2010}}</ref>
{{clear}}
==Reception== {{Video game reviews | title = Back to Stone | subtitle = <!--Formatting--> | state = plain | align = right <!-- Aggregators --> | MC = 55/100<ref name=MC>[http://www.metacritic.com/game/game-boy-advance/back-to-stone ''Back to stone''{{'}}s Metacritic page]</ref> <!-- Reviewers --> | GameZone = 6.8/10<ref name=Gamezone>{{cite web|author=N Amer|title=Back to Stone Review|url=http://gameboy.gamezone.com/gzreviews/r31078.htm|website=GameZone|accessdate=September 11, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100507055801/http://gameboy.gamezone.com/gzreviews/r31078.htm|archivedate=May 7, 2010|date=December 12, 2006}}</ref> | GSpot = 5.5/10<ref name=GSpot>{{cite web|last=Provo|first=Frank|title=Back to Stone Review|url=http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/back-to-stone-review/1900-6166565/|website=[[GameSpot]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=September 11, 2015|date=February 28, 2007}}</ref> <!-- Custom Reviewers limit is set to 10--> | rev6 = Gaming Nexus | rev6Score = F<ref name=Nexus>{{cite web|last1=Colleli|first1=Sean|title=Back to Stone Review|url=http://www.gamingnexus.com/Default.aspx?Section=Article&I=1456|website=Gaming Nexus|accessdate=September 11, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100528234544/http://www.gamingnexus.com/Default.aspx?Section=Article&I=1456|archivedate=May 28, 2010|date=April 11, 2007}}</ref> | rev1 = Pockett Videogames | rev1Score = {{stars|4|5}}<ref name=Pockett>{{cite web|author=Olivier B.|title=Back to Stone|url=http://www.pockett.net/t428_GBA_Back_to_Stone|website=Pockett Videogames|accessdate=September 11, 2015|language=French|date=January 31, 2007}}</ref> | rev2 = [[Jeuxvideo.com]] | rev2Score = 14/20<ref name=JV.com>{{cite web|title=Test : Back To Stone|url=http://www.jeuxvideo.com/articles/0000/00007225-back-to-stone-test.htm|website=[[Jeuxvideo.com]]|language=French|publisher=Webedia|accessdate=September 11, 2015|date=December 22, 2006}}</ref> | rev3 = The Entertainment Depot | rev3Score = 2/10<ref name=EntDepot>{{cite web|last1=Napolitano|first1=Jayson|title=(GBA) Back to Stone|url=http://www.entdepot.com/handheld/article_2074.php|website=The Entertainment Depot|accessdate=September 11, 2015|date=February 27, 2007}}</ref> | rev5 = Thunderbolt | rev5Score = 3/10<ref name=Thunder>{{cite web|last1=Boot|first1=Justin|title=Back to Stone|url=http://www.thunderboltgames.com/reviews/viewreview.php?rid=951|website=Thunderbolt|accessdate=September 11, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080220032938/http://www.thunderboltgames.com/reviews/viewreview.php?rid=951|archivedate=February 20, 2008|date=February 2, 2007}}{{Unreliable source?|date=September 2015}}</ref> }} The game received mixed and negative reviews. Most critics considered the gameplay to be "simple" and "familiar",<ref name="Jeuxpo" /><ref name="NSpin" /> but the stone-pushing puzzles to be "unimaginative", unoriginal, and repetitive.<ref name="JustRPG" /><ref name=Gamezone /><ref name=GSpot /><ref name=Thunder />
Some reviewers considered the graphics and design to be "charming and varied",<ref name="Jeuxpo" /> easy to discern (in contrast to ''[[Banjo-Kazooie: Grunty's Revenge]]''),<ref name="NSpin" /><ref name=JV.com /><ref name=Thunder /> but many judged the presentation to be "drab", "grainy" and "muddy".<ref name="NSpin" /><ref name=Nexus /><ref name=EntDepot /><ref name=Thunder /> The game's smooth framerate and special effects have received praise,<ref name="JustRPG" /><ref name=Gamezone /><ref name=Pockett /> as have the intricate boss battles.<ref name=Gamezone /><ref name=GSpot /><ref name=EntDepot />
Several reviewers have noted that controlling the character from the game's [[Isometric graphics in video games and pixel art|isometric 3D perspective]] was very difficult and "unintuitive" because of the rigidity of a [[directional pad]] and the difficulty in judging depth.<ref name="Jeuxpo" /><ref name="NSpin" /><ref name=GSpot /><ref name=Pockett /><ref name=JV.com/><ref name=EntDepot /><ref name=Thunder /> Multiple critics have praised the game's length (estimated between 8 and 15 hours), which is considered good for a portable game.<ref name="Jeuxpo" /><ref name="NSpin" /><ref name=Nexus /><ref name=GSpot /><ref name=Pockett /> The translation's poor quality has also been criticized.<ref name=JustRPG /><ref name=Gamezone />
''Back to Stone'' was heavily criticized almost unanimously for its lack of saving functionality, instead relying on a password-based system to track the player's progress, which was seen as a "cumbersome" flaw for a game on a handheld console, as well as "stupefying", "unforgivable" and "inexcusably archaic" when compared to other games released in this era.<ref name="NSpin">{{cite web |last=Nielsen |first=Clark |title=Back to Stone Game Boy Review |url=http://www.nintendospin.com/reviews/gameboy/1741/back-to-stone.html |publisher=Nintendo Spin |accessdate=September 11, 2015 |date=December 31, 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080727024130/http://www.nintendospin.com/reviews/gameboy/1741/back-to-stone.html |archivedate=July 27, 2008}}</ref><ref name=Nexus /><ref name="JustRPG" /><ref name=Gamezone /><ref name=GSpot /><ref name=JV.com /><ref name=EntDepot /><ref name=Thunder />
