In a work of media adapted from a real or fictional narrative, a '''composite character''' is a character based on more than one individual from the preceding story.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gutkind|first1=Lee|last2=Fletcher|first2=Hattie|title=Keep It Real: Everything You Need to Know About Researching and Writing Creative Nonfiction|date=2008|publisher=W.W. Norton|location=New York|isbn=0393065618|page=39|edition=1st}}</ref> Two or more fictional characters are often combined into a single character in the course of an adaptation of a work for a different medium, as in adapting a novel in the course of authoring a screenplay for a [[film adaptation|film]].{{Citation needed|date=October 2016}} A composite character may be modeled on [[historical]] or [[biographical]] figures. An '''amalgamation''' or '''amalgam''', when used to refer to a fictional character or place, refers to one that was created by combining, or is perceived to be a combination, of several other previously existing characters or locations.{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}} To emphasize the origin of their creations, authors or artists may use [[Amalgamation (names)|amalgamated names]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}}

==Use in film==
*[[Major (United States)|Major]] [[Frank Burns (M*A*S*H character)|Frank Burns]] in the 1970 film ''[[M*A*S*H (film)|M*A*S*H]]'' is a composite of [[Captain (United States)#U.S. Army, U.S. Air Force, and U.S. Marine Corps|Captain]] Frank Burns and Major Hobson from [[MASH: A Novel About Three Army Doctors|the original novel]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2013}} The composite character was carried over into [[M*A*S*H (TV series)|the TV series]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2013}}
*Chico in the 1960 film ''[[The Magnificent Seven]]'' is a composite of the samurai Kikuchiyo and Katsushiro from the film ''[[Seven Samurai]]'', which ''Magnificent Seven'' was based upon.{{Citation needed|date=October 2016}}
*Disney's version of the [[Queen of Hearts (Alice's Adventures in Wonderland)#Disney|Queen of Hearts]], as seen in [[Alice in Wonderland (1951 film)|the 1951 adaptation of ''Alice in Wonderland'']], seems to be an amalgam of the [[Duchess (Alice's Adventures in Wonderland)|Duchess]] and the Queen in ''[[Alice's Adventures in Wonderland]]'', and the [[Red Queen (Through the Looking Glass)|Red Queen]] of ''[[Through The Looking-Glass]]''. Also, the [[The Dormouse#Disney version|Dormouse]] is an amalgam of the [[Mouse (Alice's Adventures in Wonderland)|Mouse]] and the Dormouse.{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}}
*The character Robert Ciaro in the [[biographical film]] ''[[Hoffa]]'', is an amalgamation of several [[Jimmy Hoffa]] associates over the years.{{Citation needed|date=October 2016}}
*Several characters in the movie ''[[21 (2008 film)|21]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.boston.com/bostonglobe/ideas/articles/2008/04/06/house_of_cards/ |title=House of cards |publisher=Boston.com |date=6 April 2008 |accessdate=13 October 2013}}{{subscription required}}</ref><!--which characters are composites needs including-->
*Many of the characters in the film ''[[Black Hawk Down (film)|Black Hawk Down]]'' are composites, including the protagonist Matt Eversmann.{{Citation needed|date=March 2013}}
*The character Henry Hurt in the [[docudrama]] ''[[Apollo 13 (film)|Apollo 13]]'' is portrayed as a [[NASA]] [[public relations]] employee assigned to the wife of astronaut [[Jim Lovell]], and who also is seen answering reporters' questions. This character is a composite of the [[NASA]] protocol officer Bob McMurrey assigned to act as a buffer between the Lovell family and the press, and several [[Office of Public Affairs]] employees whose job was to actually work with the press.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Lovell|first1=Jim|last2=Kluger|first2=Jeffrey|authorlink2=Jeffrey Kluger|title=Apollo 13|date=1994|publisher=Pocket Books|location=New York|isbn=0671534645|pages=118, 209–210, 387}}</ref>
* [[Buffalo Bill (character)|Buffalo Bill]] in ''[[The Silence of the Lambs (film)|The Silence of the Lambs]]'' is a composite based on the [[serial killers]] [[Jerry Brudos]], [[Ed Gein]], [[Ted Bundy]], [[Gary M. Heidnik]], [[Edmund Kemper]], and [[Gary Ridgway]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Grow|first1=Kory|title='Silence of the Lambs' at 25: Inside Buffalo Bill|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/silence-of-the-lambs-at-25-the-complete-buffalo-bill-story-20160214|website=Rolling Stone|accessdate=2016-05-24|date=2016-02-14}}</ref>
*The character Friedrich Sternberg in the 2008 film ''[[The Red Baron (2008 film)|The Red Baron]]'', is a composite of the many Jewish pilots who fought for the German Empire in the First World War.{{Citation needed|date=February 2017}}
*The character Peter Brand in the 2011 film ''[[Moneyball (film)|Moneyball]]'', played by Jonah Hill, was a composite of Peter Brand and his real life assistant Paul DePodesta.{{Citation needed|date=April 2017}}
*Lucy in 2016's ''[[Lion (2016 film)|Lion]]'' is a composite of several of Saroo Brierley's acquaintances.{{Citation needed|date=July 2017}}
*The character Commander Bolton in the 2017 film ''[[Dunkirk (2017 film)|Dunkirk]]'' is a composite of several real life people, including Commander [[James Campbell Clouston]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Alexander|first1=Bryan|title='Dunkirk': How historically accurate is Christopher Nolan's WWII battle film?|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2017/07/20/dunkirk-how-historically-accurate-christopher-nolans-wwii-film/493068001|accessdate=22 January 2018|work=USA TODAY|date=20 July 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref name="montrealgazette">{{cite news |url=http://montrealgazette.com/news/local-news/inspiration-for-summer-blockbuster-dunkirk-an-unsung-montreal-hero |title=Inspiration for summer blockbuster Dunkirk an unsung Montreal hero |first=René |last=Bruemmer |newspaper=[[Montreal Gazette]] |date=2 August 2017 |accessdate=2 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-4726774/The-real-hero-Dunkirk-Courage-pier-master.html |first=Guy |last=Adams |title=The real hero of Dunkirk: Courage of the pier-master who manned a crucial jetty to organise evacuees for six days and five nights without a break |newspaper=[[The Daily Mail]] |date=25 July 2017 |accessdate=4 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://publications.mcgill.ca/reporter/2017/08/unsung-hero-of-dunkirk-evacuation-a-mcgill-student |title=Unsung hero of Dunkirk evacuation a former McGill student |date=7 August 2017 |website=McGill Reporter |publisher=[[McGill University]] |accessdate=4 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2017/09/21/this-war-hero-was-forgotten-in-canada-and-portrayed-as-a-brit-in-dunkirk-now-hes-finally-getting-his-due/ |title=This war hero was forgotten in Canada and portrayed as a Brit in ‘Dunkirk.’ Now he’s finally getting his due |newspaper=Washington Post |date=September 21, 2017}}</ref> and Captain [[William Tennant (Royal Navy officer)|Bill Tennant]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://amp.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2017/07/20/what_s_fact_and_what_s_fiction_in_dunkirk.html |title=What's Fact and What's Fiction in 'Dunkirk' |last=Broich |first=John |date=20 July 2017 |website=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |access-date=25 March 2018}}</ref>
*[[Glinda the Good Witch#1939_film|Glinda the Good Witch of the North]] in the 1939 film ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1939 film)|The Wizard of Oz]]'' is a composite of the [[Good Witch of the North]] and Glinda the Good Witch of the South from ''[[The Wonderful Wizard of Oz]]''.
*The characters in the 1963 film ''[[The Great Escape (film)|The Great Escape]]'' are based on real men, and in some cases are composites of several men. The character Virgil Hilts, the "Cooler King," was based on at least three pilots, [[David M. Jones]], John Dortch Lewis,<ref>{{cite news|last=Kaufman |first=Michael T. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/08/13/world/john-d-lewis-84-pilot-in-the-great-escape.html |title=John D. Lewis, 84, Pilot in 'The Great Escape' |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=August 13, 1999 |accessdate=March 15, 2015}}</ref> and [[William Ash (writer)|William Ash]].<ref name="BBC Online 30 August 2015">{{cite web | title= William Ash: The cooler king |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-34058540| last= Bishop| first= Patrick| date= 30 August 2015| website= [[BBC Online]] | accessdate= 30 August 2015}}</ref><ref name="The Guardian 29 April 2014">{{cite news | first= Brendan |last= Foley| url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/apr/29/bill-ash | title= Bill Ash obituary| newspaper= [[The Guardian]] | location= London| date= 29 April 2014| accessdate= 30 August 2015}}</ref><ref name="Daily Telegraph 30 April 2014">{{cite news | author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/10799031/William-Ash-obituary.html | title= William Ash - obituary | newspaper= [[The Daily Telegraph]] | location= London| date= 30 April 2014| accessdate= 30 August 2015}}</ref>

==Use in musicals==
*The musical version of ''[[Les Misérables (musical)|Les Misérables]]'' has the [[charisma]]tic revolutionary [[Enjolras]] die while waving a flag at the top of a barricade; in the [[Les Misérables|original novel]] by [[Victor Hugo]], a character named Mabeuf dies in such a way.{{Citation needed|date=October 2016}}
*The musical ''Wicked'' has the character of Fiyero who fills in the roles of both himself (the love interest of the Wicked With of the West) and another minor character from the novel.
*In the musical ''Legally Blonde,'' the character of Professor Stromwell from the film does not appear.  Her storyline is split up between Vivian and Professor Callahan.

==Use in television==
* The main antagonist of the fifth season of ''[[Arrow (TV series)|Arrow]],'' Simon Morrison, poses as the villainous warrior [[Prometheus (DC Comics)|Prometheus]] as well as the Star City District Attourney [[Vigilante (comics)|Adrian Chase]].{{Citation needed|date=November 2017}}
*[[First Lieutenant|1st Lt.]] (later [[Captain (United States O-3)|CPT]]) [[Colleen McMurphy]] on the television series ''[[China Beach]]'' was a composite of several real-life [[Nurse Corps (United States Army)|Army nurses]] who served in [[Vietnam War|Vietnam]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Goodykoontz|first1=Billy|title=25 years later, 'China Beach' earns your respect|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2013/05/28/television-china-beach/2367887/|website=USA TODAY|accessdate=2016-05-24|language=en|date=2013-05-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/entertainment/2013/09/china-beach-cast-reunites-reflects-on-series-impact/|title='China Beach': Cast Reunites, Reflects on Series' Impact|publisher=ABC News|date=2013-09-30|accessdate=2016-05-24}}</ref>
*[[Savitar (comics)|Savitar]] in ''[[The Flash (2014 TV series)|The Flash]]'' television series is depicted as a possible future version of [[Flash (Barry Allen)|Barry Allen/The Flash]].{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}} Savitar's costume, a dark suit covered in glowing blue lines, is based off the costume of Barry's future self from the [[The New 52|New 52 comics]].{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}}
*[[Marshall Matt Dillon]] on ''[[Gunsmoke]]'' is a composite of several [[list of Old West lawmen|Old West Kansas lawmen]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Allen|last=Barra |url=http://www.americanheritage.com/content/dodge-vs-deadwood |title=Dodge Vs. Deadwood |work=American Heritage |date=July 2013 |accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref>
*Chris's siblings Drew and Tonya from ''[[Everybody Hates Chris]]'' are based off [[Chris Rock]]'s seven real-life siblings.{{Citation needed|date=October 2016}}
*[[Shocker (comics)|The Shocker]] in ''[[Spectacular Spider-Man (TV series)|Spectacular Spider-Man]]'' combines both the comics version of the character and a separate, unrelated Spider-Man villain [[Montana (comics)|Jackson "Montana" Brice]]. Similarly, [[Fancy Dan]] is a composite of the comic character and [[Ricochet (comics)|Ricochet]], one of the various identities assumed by Peter Parker.{{Citation needed|date=July 2017}}
*[[Professor James Moriarty|Jamie Moriarty]] in ''[[Elementary (TV series)|Elementary]]'' is a composite character of both [[Professor Moriarty]] and [[Irene Adler]] from [[Arthur Conan Doyle|Sir Arthur Conan Doyle]]'s original novels.

==Use in books==
* ''The Senator: My Ten Years with Ted Kennedy'', a memoir by Richard E. Burke allegedly exposing various activities of U.S. Senator [[Teddy Kennedy]] featured several composite characters associated with Kennedy's alleged drug use and sexual dalliances; the inclusion of such became a point of criticism for the book.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.philly.com/1992-09-27/news/26022267_1_kara-kennedy-allen-cocaine-massachusetts-democrat |title=Ex-aide's Book Alleges Kennedy Used Drugs The Senator Called Allegations About Orgies, Drugs And Alcohol "Bizarre And Untrue" |publisher=The Inquirer |date=27 September 1992 |accessdate=25 October 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306215234/http://articles.philly.com/1992-09-27/news/26022267_1_kara-kennedy-allen-cocaine-massachusetts-democrat |archive-date=6 March 2016 |dead-url=yes |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Isaak |first=Sharon |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,312212,00.html |title=Tales of Ted Kennedy |publisher=Entertainment Weekly |date=30 October 1992 |accessdate=25 October 2015}}</ref>

==Use in comics==
*All the [[Amalgam Comics#Amalgam characters|characters]] from [[Amalgam Comics]] are combinations of superheroes from [[Marvel Comics]] and [[DC Comics]], such as [[Super-Soldier]] ([[Captain America]] + [[Superman]]) and [[Dark Claw]] ([[Wolverine (character)|Wolverine]] + [[Batman]]).<ref name="Marvel graphic novels and related publications">{{cite book |title=Marvel graphic novels and related publications: an annotated guide to comics, prose novels, children's books, articles, criticism and reference works |last=Weiner |first=Robert G. |date=2008 |publisher=McFarland |location= |isbn=978-0-7864-2500-6 |pages=228, 385|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=npIsZV7grboC |accessdate=March 23, 2011}}</ref>

==Use in journalism==
Creating composite characters in [[journalism]] is considered a misrepresentation of facts and, without appropriate notice to the reader, [[Journalism ethics and standards|unethical]].{{Citation needed|date=November 2017}} Some writers who are considered journalists or who describe them selves as journalists have on occasion used composite characters.{{Citation needed|date=October 2016}}

*In 1944, ''[[The New Yorker]]'' ran a series of articles by [[Joseph Mitchell (writer)|Joseph Mitchell]] on [[New York, New York|New York]]'s [[Fulton Fish Market]] that were presented as journalism. Only when the story was published four years later as the book ''Old Mr. Flood'' did Mitchell write, "Mr. Flood is not one man; combined in him are aspects of several old men who work or hang out in Fulton Fish Market, or who did in the past."<ref>{{cite web|last=Shafer |first=Jack |url=http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/press_box/2003/06/the_fabulous_fabulists.html |title=The fabulous fabulists |publisher=Slate|date=12 June 2003 |accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref> Mitchell assigned his composite character his own birthday and his own love for the [[Bible]] and certain authors.<ref name=TNC>{{cite news|url=http://www.newcriterion.com/archive/11/nov92/mitchell.htm | date=3 November 1992 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010306202907/http://www.newcriterion.com/archive/11/nov92/mitchell.htm| first=Christopher | last= Carduff| accessdate=12 May 2016 | dead-url=yes | work=New Criterion|archive-date=6 March 2001 | title= Fish-eating, whiskey, death & rebirth }}</ref> In his introduction to ''Mr. Flood'', Mitchell wrote, "I wanted these stories to be truthful rather than factual, but they are solidly based on facts."<ref name=Slate2>{{cite web|last=O'Rourke |first=Meghan |url=http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/culturebox/2003/07/literary_license.html |title=Literary license |publisher=Slate |date=29 July 2003 |accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref>
*[[John Hersey]] is said to have created a composite character in a ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'' magazine story as did [[Alastair Reid]] for ''The New Yorker''.<ref name=Slate2/>
*[[Vivian Gornick]] in 2003 said that she used composite characters in some of her articles for the ''[[Village Voice]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wtopnews.com/index.php?nid=114&sid=671980 |title=Unethical writers love the power of creative non-fiction - |publisher=WTOP.com |date=13 January 2006 |accessdate=13 October 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926212116/http://www.wtopnews.com/index.php?nid=114&sid=671980 |archive-date=26 September 2007 |dead-url=yes |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

==Amalgamated places==
{{See also|Amalgamation (politics)}}
Places may be amalgamated in fiction by taking districts, [[landmark]]s, or characters of existing locations, or previously created locations of another work of fiction. Thus, a sample fictional city could contain the [[Eiffel Tower]] a block away from the [[Forbidden City]], where [[Bill Gates]] may be living after having bought a nearby [[Technology of the Discworld#The clacks|clacks]] tower from [[Albus Dumbledore]]. Usually, if the author or artist desires the city to be more [[suspension of disbelief|believable]], he or she will amalgam it only from real places, whereas if the story is more [[fantasy|fantastic]], fictional places may be better.

An author or artist may choose to amalgamate a city rather than imagining all of its aspects from scratch in order to be humorous by referencing other works and/or real places, or to avoid having to name his or her city altogether, such as when [[Filmmaking#Production|shooting]] a film in several existing cities, while the city portrayed is supposed not to exist.

