{{Infobox baseball biography |name=Harry Bay |position=[[Outfielder]] |image= |bats=Left |throws=Left |birth_date={{Birth date|1878|1|17}} |birth_place=[[Pontiac, Illinois]] |death_date={{death date and age|1952|3|19|1878|1|17}} |death_place=[[Peoria, Illinois]]<ref name="gpshof" /> |debutleague = MLB |debutdate= July 23 |debutyear= 1901 |debutteam= Cincinnati Reds |finalleague = MLB |finaldate=May 3 |finalyear=1908 |finalteam= Cleveland Naps |statleague = MLB |stat1label=[[Batting average]] |stat1value=.273 |stat2label=[[Home run]]s |stat2value=5 |stat3label=[[Run batted in|Runs batted in]] |stat3value=141 |stat4label=[[Stolen bases]] |stat4value=169 |teams= * [[Cincinnati Reds]] ({{Baseball year|1901}}–{{Baseball year|1902}}) * [[Cleveland Indians|Cleveland Bronchos/Naps]] ({{Baseball year|1902}}–{{Baseball year|1908}}) |highlights= * 2× [[List of Major League Baseball annual stolen base leaders|AL stolen base leader]] (1903, 1904) }}
'''Harry Elbert "Deerfoot" Bay''' (January 17, 1878 – March 19, 1952)<ref name="gpshof">{{cite web | url = http://www.gpshof.org/Inductees/bay.html | title = Harry Bay | publisher = Greater Peoria Sports Hall of Fame, Inc. | location = Peoria, Illinois | date = 2008-04-21 | accessdate = 2008-12-10 }}</ref> was a professional baseball player who played [[outfield]] in the [[Major League Baseball|Major Leagues]] from 1901 to 1908. Bay played for the [[Cincinnati Reds]] and [[Cleveland Indians|Cleveland Bronchos/Naps]].
He attended [[Peoria High School (Peoria, Illinois)|Peoria High School]], winning medals in the 1896 and 1897 [[Illinois High School Association]] state [[track and field]] meets. After retiring from baseball in 1908, he returned to Peoria, became a bandleader at the local Apollo Theater, and toured the [[vaudeville]] circuit with [[Guy Kibbee]]. He later worked for the Peoria fire department and the [[Illinois Secretary of State]].<ref name="gpshof" />
