'''Richard Noel Marshall Armitage''' (12 August 1928&nbsp;&ndash; 17 November 1986)<ref name=obit>{{cite news | author =<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> | title = Mr Richard Armitage | url = http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=bright&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=IF501704597&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0 | newspaper = The Times | location = London, England | date = 20 November 1986 | page = 22 | via = The Times Digital Archive | subscription = yes | accessdate = 2014-08-05 }}</ref><ref name="NGA">{{cite web|url=http://www.noelgay.com/about-us|title=About Us|publisher=[[Noel Gay Artists]]|accessdate=9 August 2013}}</ref> was a [[talent agent]], active in England in the 1950s–1980s. Among his clients were [[Rowan Atkinson]], [[John Cleese]], [[David Frost]] and [[Stephen Fry]].<ref name="NA">{{Cite episode | title = Not Again: Not the Nine O'Clock News | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/b00pl0w6/Not_Again_Not_the_Nine_O'Clock_News/ | accessdate = 2013-08-03 | network = [[BBC Television]] | date = 2013-08-03 | series =Not the Nine O'Clock News }}</ref> Producer [[John Lloyd (producer)|John Lloyd]] described him as "the most powerful agent in the country at that time [the late 1970s]".<ref name="NA" />
Armitage's father was songwriter and music publisher [[Noel Gay]], (born Reginald Moxon Armitage),<ref name="NGA" /> and in the late 1950s Richard set up [[Noel Gay Artists]] in order to ensure a supply of performers for his father's compositions.<ref name="NGA" />
In the 1960s, NGA's clients included [[Russ Conway]], [[Peter & Gordon]], [[The Scaffold]], [[Geoff Love]], [[Paul Jones (singer)|Paul Jones]], David Frost, and John Cleese.<ref name="NGA" />
In the 1970s [[The King's Singers]], [[The Swingle Singers]], [[Tony Macaulay]], [[Jake Thackray]] and [[Claude François]] were on the company's books.<ref name="NGA" />
Armitage died of a heart attack at his home in [[Stebbing]] in 1986.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1986/11/19/obituaries/richard-armitage-producer-and-agent-dies.html RICHARD ARMITAGE, PRODUCER AND AGENT, DIES, By JEREMY GERARD, ''New York Times'', Published: November 19] Retrieved 2016-10-18.</ref> His sons Charles and Alex, who had joined the agency in 1972 and 1976 respectively, continued the business.
